## Building a Multi-select Dropdown in React

**Mental model:** A multi-select is a toggleable panel of checkable options where the selection is a `Set` of values. The trigger summarizes the selection ("2 selected"); the panel toggles membership. Close on outside-click. Keep it controlled — parent owns the selected array.

### Step 1 — Open state + selection as a Set
```jsx
const [open, setOpen] = useState(false);
const selectedSet = new Set(value);
```

### Step 2 — Toggle membership
```jsx
const toggle = (v) => {
  const next = new Set(value);
  next.has(v) ? next.delete(v) : next.add(v);
  onChange([...next]);
};
```

### Step 3 — Close on outside click
A document `mousedown` listener that closes when the click is outside the root ref.

```jsx
useEffect(() => {
  const onDoc = (e) => { if (root.current && !root.current.contains(e.target)) setOpen(false); };
  document.addEventListener('mousedown', onDoc);
  return () => document.removeEventListener('mousedown', onDoc);
}, []);
```

### Step 4 — Summarize the trigger
```jsx
const label = value.length === 0 ? 'Select…' : `${value.length} selected`;
```

**Edge cases**

| Case | Handling |
| :-- | :-- |
| Click inside panel | `contains` check keeps it open. |
| Select all / clear | Set `onChange` to all values or `[]`. |
| Listener leak | Effect cleanup removes the document handler. |

**Interview tip:** The outside-click-to-close pattern (a document listener + a `ref.contains` check, cleaned up on unmount) is reusable across dropdowns/popovers — calling that out shows you've built real overlay UI.

