## Building a Multi-select Dropdown in Angular

**Mental model:** A multi-select is a toggleable panel of checkable options; the selection is an array (membership via `indexOf`). The trigger summarizes it; clicking an option toggles membership; an outside click closes it. Controlled via `selected` in + `selectedChange` out. Classic `NgModule` setup, no `?.`/`??` (the build rejects them).

### Step 1 — Open state + I/O
```typescript
open = false;
@Input() options: Option[] = [];
@Input() selected: string[] = [];
@Output() selectedChange = new EventEmitter<string[]>();
```

### Step 2 — Toggle membership
```typescript
toggle(v: string): void {
  const set = new Set(this.selected);
  if (set.has(v)) { set.delete(v); } else { set.add(v); }
  this.selectedChange.emit([...set]);
}
isOn(v: string): boolean { return this.selected.indexOf(v) !== -1; }
```

### Step 3 — Close on outside click
A `@HostListener('document:click')` closes when the click is outside the host element.

```typescript
@HostListener('document:click', ['$event'])
onDoc(e: MouseEvent): void {
  if (!this.host.nativeElement.contains(e.target)) { this.open = false; }
}
```

### Step 4 — Summarize the trigger
```html
<button (click)="open = !open">{{ selected.length ? selected.length + ' selected' : 'Select…' }}</button>
```

**Edge cases**

| Case | Handling |
| :-- | :-- |
| Click inside | `contains` check keeps it open. |
| Toggle-then-close | Stop propagation or rely on contains. |
| Cleanup | `@HostListener` auto-unbinds on destroy. |

**Interview tip:** `@HostListener('document:click')` + `ElementRef.nativeElement.contains` is Angular's clean outside-click recipe — and it auto-removes the listener when the component is destroyed, so no manual teardown.

